title: CATER 155509, Kly Mod 14-5: excessive phase and amplitude jitter.
text: Kly Mod 14-5: station reports excessive phase and amplitude jitter. Reservoir @ 7.75. Ranged all the way to 8.35 volts--no change. BV + PFN waveforms very unstable. Removed thyratron L4888 S/N 100846 from spare station 02-4 next to 14-5. After time in, discovered tube is shorted. Removed triggers: thyratron is dead shorted--HV will not get above 1-2 KV without HVOC hard faulting. HV RTM @ 02-4 = 57325 hrs. Replaced thyratron with L4888 S/N 100779 removed from spare mod 03-2 next to 11-4. HV RTM @ 03-2 = 59814 hrs. BV and PFN waveforms very stable. New used thyratron works very well @ eres of 3.7 volts. MM = 7.2%. KA = 289 mA. DQ = 11 amps. HVDC = 19.5 KV @ .8 amps. 14-5 HV RTM = 59698 hr. CATER ready to close.

title: PLIC was frozen, temporary fix inside:
text: This should only be a temporary fix, but we think that the signal we see is real. The scope (IN10 FC02) was originally triggering on channel 4, but that channel is just a flat line. We're not sure if it was always this way, but presumably it wasn't. Ahmed changed it so it triggers on itself (channel 1), and then moved the level value around so the signal/image looks like what we would expect. The shape of the signal is different - it goes up, then down, while before, there would just be a dip where there was beam loss. But we confirmed it responds with beam, so this is good enough for now.

title: Found the phase of 19-4 and 19-5 had the wrong sign...I think
text: We found that when we tried to move the LI20 energy multi-knob, the energy BPMs in LI20 didn't move. We found that 19-4 PDES was set to -45deg and 19-5 PDES was set to +45deg. The multi-knob file for the LI20 energy (S20_ENERGY_4AND5.MKB) is set such that 19-4 has a positive coefficient and 19-5 has a negative coefficient. Operating on the assumption that 19-4 should be positive and 19-5 should be negative, we changed 19-4 to -45deg and 19-5 to +45deg. After making these changes, the knob seems to control the energy the way it's supposed to. I guess this is another thing to look out for in the future.
